To cure some of your bafflement (=P) :<br>
- First of all, many anti-war people are not saying to doing totally nothing no matter what.<br>
- the &quot;very real security risk&quot; is really subjective.<br>
<br>
As far as terrorism goes, this war may possibly cut some access to terror-weaponry off from Al Qaida. But access to weaponry has never been one of terrorism's strengths. Their strength lies in going for non-military targets with any means available to them. I mean, cardboard cutters were used in 9/11 - the really important factor in 9/11 was the funding (which the US has been trying to make difficult ever since, with success I believe) and the way they used unconventional weapons.<br>
<br>
What I consider more serious is that I think that Al Qaida has found many more believers for their cause. I think that is much more dangerous than cutting off some chemical weaponry, which to my knowledge (although I admit, I can't really judge this) is relatively easy obtained elsewhere.<br>
<br>
You know, the US had a LOT of support just after 9/11 - I can't help but think, couldn't this strong power they had then (not military, but political power) be used to create stability in the region ? None of that remains and the global support is actually worse than it has ever been since the end of the Cold War.<br>
<br>
